MissionCommands.Message: Welcome to the Reaction Control System lesson of the Lunar Module Academy. Press F4 to enter the Lunar Module.
The RCS is used to control the attitude and translation of the spacecraft.
Attitude and translation are controlled with 16 RCS thrust chamber assemblies (TCA's).
The TCA's can receive propellant from the RCS propellant supplies or by propellants from the ascent propulsion section.

The RCS consists of two parallel, independent systems (A and B), which, under normal conditions, function simultaneously. Each system has its own pressurized propellant supply that feeds two of the thrusters in eight TCA's
Fuel and oxidizer are loaded into bladders within the propellant tanks, pressurized by helium.
The RCS propellant tanks are pressurized immediately before separation of the LM from the CSM, by firing of explosive valves by the Explosive Devices Subsystem (EDS).
Let's learn how to pressurize the RCS system now. First of all, arm the MASTER ARM switch on the Explosives Devices on panel 8.
Approximately 1 pound of gaseous helium, at a nominal pressure of 3,050 psia at +70° F, is stored in the helium tank.
This will be used to pressurize the RCS once we open the valves. Do this by setting the He PRESS RCS switch to FIRE.
Helium now flows into the RCS system. We can monitor the Helium pressure by using the TEMP/PRESS MON selector on the bottom-left side of Panel 2. Verify that this is set to He.
The REACTION CONTROL gauges on the upper-left side of Panel 2 is used to monitor the RCS. When set to He, the value on the RCS PRESS gauge needs to be multiplied by 10.
32 heaters are used to heat the 16 TCA's. Each TCA has two heaters, and these are controlled by 8 different circuit breakers. Let's take a closer look at this.
You can control individual heaters by opening the HEATERS RCS SYS A/B 1/2 circuit breakers. First, open the RCS SYS A/B - 1 Quad 4 heater on Panel 11.
Next open the RCS SYS A/B - 2 Quad 4 heater on Panel 16.
Verify that the other three circuit breakers, for Q1, Q2 and Q3 is closed, and both Q4 circuit breakers are open.
We will leave Q4 open for a while now, but please remember that all of these circuit breakers are usually closed.
The main heater controls are located on Panel 3, and is usually set to AUTO. Set Quad 4 to OFF.
These controls also provide manual control of the heaters. MAN will set the heaters to ON, and OFF will disable the heater. Auto will try to keep the temperature within limits, and above 120° F.
Primary power (28 volts) is applied to the TCA primary coils via the RCS SYS A and RCS SYS B: QUAD TCA circuit breakers on panel 11 and panel 16.
Verify RCS SYS A, QUAD 1 TCA on panel 11 is closed.
Verify RCS SYS A, QUAD 2 TCA is closed.
Verify RCS SYS A, QUAD 3 TCA is closed.
Verify RCS SYS A, QUAD 4 TCA is closed.
Verify RCS SYS B, QUAD 1 TCA is closed.
Verify RCS SYS B, QUAD 2 TCA is closed.
Verify RCS SYS B, QUAD 3 TCA is closed.
Verify RCS SYS B, QUAD 4 TCA is closed.
With all of the TCS powered, all that remains is to open the reactant valves, so propellant and fuel gets to each of them.
Set the SYSTEM A THRUSTER PAIR QUAD 1 on panel 2 to OPEN to open the valve.
Set the SYSTEM A THRUSTER PAIR QUAD 2 on panel 2 to OPEN.
Set the SYSTEM A THRUSTER PAIR QUAD 3 on panel 2 to OPEN.
Set the SYSTEM A THRUSTER PAIR QUAD 4 on panel 2 to OPEN.
Set the SYSTEM B THRUSTER PAIR QUAD 1 on panel 2 to OPEN.
Set the SYSTEM B THRUSTER PAIR QUAD 2 on panel 2 to OPEN.
Set the SYSTEM B THRUSTER PAIR QUAD 3 on panel 2 to OPEN.
Set the SYSTEM B THRUSTER PAIR QUAD 4 on panel 2 to OPEN.
Next, we need to open the main shutoff valve by setting the MAIN SOV SYS A switch to OPEN.
And the MAIN SOV SYS B switch to OPEN as well.
We will get more into the flight modes later, but for this lesson, we will set the PITCH attitude control mode to PULSE. This is done on panel 3 under STAB/CONT.
You should now be able to pitch the spacecraft using [W] and [S] (default bindings). The PULSE mode will only fire the jet briefly for each deflection.
Now, cancel your pitch rates and get back into the spacecraft.
Use the TEMP MONITOR selector on Panel 3 to cycle through the temperatures on each QUAD.
Notice that Quad 1, Quad 2 and Quad 3 should have a temperature within range (up to 160F), while Quad 4 will be quite low as the heaters has been disabled.
It is important that the temperatures in the quads are over 125F before using the RCS system.
The RCS system is mostly used by the Lunar Guidance Computer, as well as the direct modes available, and we will dive into this in the next lessons.
That's it for now, good job!

Title: Lesson 4 - Reaction Control System
Description: The Reaction Control System is used to change the attitude of the Lunar Module, as well as translating. This lesson teaches you the basics of the RCS system, while flight modes are covered in a later lesson.
BriefingText:
BRIEFING

Instructor: Patrick
Level: Advanced

In this lesson, we will go deeper into the Reaction Control System (RCS), and how it's used to control the spacecraft.
